<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900411-0065</DOCNO><DOCID>900411-0065.</DOCID><HL>   Bush Toughens His Stance   On Uprising in Lithuania</HL><DATE>04/11/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7</SO><CO>   FREST CANDA</CO><GV>EXECUTIVE (EXE)</GV><LP>   TORONTO -- President Bush, slightly toughening hisrhetoric on the uprising in Lithuania, contended that &quot;shouldthings deteriorate in Lithuania, it would be extraordinarilydifficult&quot; for U.S.-Soviet relations to improve quickly.   Mr. Bush's comments, made to reporters after he finished athree-hour meeting with Canadian Prime Minister BrianMulroney, came a day after Soviet leaders said they wouldstep up pressure in Lithuania in an effort to quell theproblems. The president's statement came just a week afterthe White House and Kremlin announced plans for a late Maysummit meeting focusing on arms accords.</LP><TEXT>   But Mr. Bush appeared to rule out any chance that thesummit might be canceled because of the Lithuania uprising,contending that &quot;when you have complications, that's a goodtime to talk.&quot;   In response to a question, the president also said thereis &quot;no trilateral agreement being discussed&quot; among the U.S.,Canada and Mexico. Mr. Bush said he was pleased that PrimeMinister Mulroney had met recently with Mexican PresidentCarlos Salinas, and that he plans to meet with Mexicanofficials soon as well.   Mr. Mulroney said he expects the U.S. and Canada to gettogether this summer to work out an acid-rain accord. He saidthe two sides are waiting for Congress to complete the ClearAir Act, which includes measures on acid rain.</TEXT></DOC>